      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How Long Does It Take to Sell a House in Brisbane?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        What 'days on market' really means, how Brisbane's inner east compares by method of sale, and what you can do to control the timeline.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When sellers ask how long it will take to sell their home, they usually mean two different things: how quickly will they get a contract signed, and when will they actually receive the proceeds. These are separate questions with different answers, and confusing them leads to unrealistic expectations about the timeline.</p>

      <p>The short answer for a well-prepared, correctly priced property in Brisbane's inner east is this: you should have a signed contract within 3 to 6 weeks of going to market. Add 30 to 60 days for a standard settlement period and the full timeline from engaging an agent to receiving funds sits somewhere between 10 and 14 weeks. What varies most is not the settlement period, which is largely fixed by contract, but how quickly the campaign generates a buyer willing to pay your price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What days on market actually measures</h2>
      <p>Days on market is a specific metric that counts the number of days between the date a property is first listed on the major portals and the date a contract is signed. It does not include the settlement period, and it resets if a property is taken off the market and relisted after a failed campaign.</p>

      <p>This reset feature matters. A property that was listed for 90 days, withdrawn, and then relisted can appear to have a days on market figure of 14 days in its second campaign. That fresh listing date obscures the full picture. When reviewing comparable sales, always ask whether the sold price came from the first campaign or a subsequent relisting, and what the combined days on market were across both attempts.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, median days on market for houses in an active market typically sits between 20 and 35 days. In a softer market, or for properties that are overpriced or poorly presented, that figure climbs quickly, sometimes past 60 or 70 days.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How method of sale affects the timeline</h2>
      <p>The method you sell by has a direct effect on how long the campaign runs before a contract is signed.</p>

      <p>Auction campaigns in Brisbane's inner east typically run for 4 weeks. If the property sells under the hammer or in negotiations immediately after, the timeline is tight and predictable. The auction date creates urgency that concentrates buyer activity into a short window. If the property passes in without a sale, the timeline extends while negotiations continue, and the early momentum that auction campaigns generate starts to dissipate.</p>

      <p>Private treaty sales are open-ended by nature. A well-priced private treaty listing in a suburb with active buyer demand can sell in the first week. An overpriced one can sit for months. The lack of a fixed end date removes the urgency that drives auction campaigns, which means price and presentation need to be sharper from day one to create the same buyer response.</p>

      <p>Expressions of interest campaigns set a closing date, typically 3 to 4 weeks from listing, and require buyers to submit written offers by that date. They combine elements of both auction and private treaty, with a defined end point but no public auction event. EOI tends to suit higher-end or unique properties where the buyer pool is smaller and more considered in their approach.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The full timeline from start to settlement</h2>
      <p>Sellers often underestimate how much time the pre-campaign phase takes. From the moment you engage an agent to the day the listing goes live, a thorough preparation process typically takes 2 to 4 weeks. This includes the appraisal, signing the agency authority (Form 6 in Queensland), getting any agreed repairs done, engaging a stylist if needed, photography, copywriting, and the portal approvals process.</p>

      <p>Rushing this phase is one of the most common and costly mistakes sellers make. A property that goes to market before it is ready, with poor photography or outstanding maintenance visible on the first open home, loses momentum it is very hard to recover. The first 2 weeks of a campaign are when the largest pool of active buyers see the listing for the first time. That window does not come again.</p>

      <p>After a contract is signed, the settlement period for most residential sales in Queensland is 30 days, though 45 to 60 days is common where the buyer requires finance approval or the seller needs time to find alternative accommodation. The settlement period is largely fixed by negotiation at the time of contract, so sellers who need certainty around their moving date should factor this into offer negotiations early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why sitting on the market hurts your price</h2>
      <p>A property that has been on the market for more than 6 weeks in Brisbane's inner east starts to develop what agents call market fatigue. Buyers who have been actively searching will have already seen it. New buyers entering the search will notice the extended days on market and start asking why. The questions that run through a buyer's mind are predictable: is there something wrong with the property that inspectors found? Is the vendor unrealistic on price? Is there a strata or legal issue?</p>

      <p>These doubts give buyers leverage. Rather than competing with other interested parties, they negotiate from a position of patience. The discounting that accompanies extended days on market is not simply a reflection of price adjustment. It is the result of a shift in the negotiating dynamic that compounds over time. Data consistently shows that properties selling after 60 or more days on market achieve meaningfully lower prices relative to initial ask than those that sell within the first 3 weeks of campaign.</p>

      <p>This is why a property sold quickly at or near asking price represents a better outcome than one that achieves a similar price after 3 months of discounting and negotiating. The end price might look similar, but the holding costs, the stress, and the negotiating position of both parties are very different.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers can do to control the timeline</h2>
      <p>Three factors drive most of the variation in days on market: pricing, presentation, and buyer demand in your specific price bracket. Of these, pricing is the most powerful lever. A property priced accurately for current market conditions will attract buyers who are ready to proceed. A property priced 10% above the market will attract lookers, generate offers well below asking, and sit longer than it should.</p>

      <p>Pricing accurately does not mean pricing low. It means pricing at the point where buyers with genuine capacity perceive the value as fair. In Brisbane's inner east, where the buyer pool for well-presented family homes is consistently active, accurate pricing tends to create competitive tension, which produces better outcomes than the aggressive anchoring strategy that many agents recommend to win the listing.</p>

      <p>Presentation is the second lever. Buyers form strong impressions quickly, and they discount hard when a property needs obvious work. Addressing the visible maintenance issues, decluttering, and investing in professional photography and styling typically reduces days on market and improves the quality of offers received. The return on that investment is well-established in the data from comparable sales.</p>

      <p>Buyer demand is the factor you have least control over, but understanding it before you list helps calibrate realistic expectations. If your suburb and price bracket has seen strong clearance rates and low days on market in recent sales, you are entering a favourable environment. If comparable properties have been sitting longer and selling with discounting, your pricing and preparation need to be tighter to overcome the current conditions.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Realistic timeframes by price bracket</h2>
      <p>As a general guide for Brisbane's inner east in a balanced market: properties under $1.2 million tend to sell fastest, typically within 2 to 4 weeks of listing, because the buyer pool is broadest and finance approval is more straightforward. Properties between $1.2 million and $2.5 million take a little longer on average, 4 to 8 weeks, reflecting a narrower buyer pool and more considered purchase decisions. Above $2.5 million, campaigns regularly run for 6 to 12 weeks, and expectations should be calibrated accordingly.</p>

      <p>These are guides, not guarantees. A well-prepared $1.8 million property in Morningside with the right method of sale and honest pricing can sell in two weeks. A $900,000 property listed 15% above the market will sit far longer and ultimately sell for less than it would have achieved with a realistic launch price.</p>

